":"1346–1400","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1392":"about 1392","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1366":"1366","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","1416":"1416","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sound","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>sound</i>,  <i>sund</i> ‘sound, healthy, prosperous’ (Old English  <i>sund</i>), for a healthy or prosperous person.","2  English: (i) locative name from Middle English  <i>sound</i>,  <i>sund</i> ‘sound (body of water, sea)’ (Old English  <i>sund</i>), for someone who lived by a sound or strait. (ii) variant of   Sand  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Bertel, Ejnar, Lars, Levinus, Nels, Niels, Thor.","English, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name for someone who lived on or near a patch of sandy soil, from the vocabulary word <i>sand</i> (German <i>Sand</i>). As a Swedish name it was often purely ornamental, and as a Jewish artificial. It is also found in France (see 3 below).","English: habitational name from a place such as Send (Surrey) or Sound (Cheshire), named with Middle English <i>sand</i>, <i>sond</i> ‘sand’."]},{"name":"Sund","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Morten, Sven.","Swedish and Danish: from <i>sund</i> ‘strait, sound’, a topographic name adopted by someone who lived by a strait or an ornamental name (often from a corresponding placename element).","Norwegian: habitational name from any of twenty-five or more farmsteads, mainly in Nordland, from Old Norse <i>sund</i> ‘strait, sound’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":14,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Sound was born in 1368, in Cheshire, England, her father, John Sounde, was 24 and her mother, Sarah Johnson, was 22. She had at least 1 daughter with David Crewe. She died in 1428, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1368–1428":"1368–1428","1366–1416":"1366–1416","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1344–1402":"1344–1402","1346–1400":"1346–1400","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1392":"umbes 1392","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1366":"1366","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","1416":"1416","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1368–1428":"1368–1428","1366–1416":"1366–1416","1392–Female":"1392–Kuollut","1344–1402":"1344–1402","1346–1400":"1346–1400","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1392":"noin 1392","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1366":"1366","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","1416":"1416","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1368–1428":"1368–1428","1366–1416":"1366–1416","1392–Female":"1392–Décédée","1344–1402":"1344–1402","1346–1400":"1346–1400","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1392":"environ 1392","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1366":"1366","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","1416":"1416","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Joan Sound est née en 1368, à Cheshire, Angleterre, son père, John Sounde, avait 24 ans et sa mère, Sarah Johnson, avait 22 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec David Crewe. Elle est décédée en 1428, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 60 ans."},"de":{"1368–1428":"1368–1428","1366–1416":"1366–1416","1392–Female":"1392–Verstorben","1344–1402":"1344–1402","1346–1400":"1346–1400","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1392":"um 1392","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1366":"1366","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1428":"1428"